f Reality TV’ -- t49 ‘Teaching Us to Fake It: The Ritualized Norms of Television’s “Reality” Games’ -- tFurther Reading -- tSection 7: News and Documentary -- tIntroduction -- t50 ‘News Values and News Production’ -- t‘The Social Production of News’ -- t52 ‘Politicizing the Personal: Women’s Voices in British Television Documentaries’ -- t53 ‘News Media and the Globalization of the Public Sphere’ -- t54 ‘Bad News from Israel’ -- t55 ‘Picturizing Science: The Science Documentary as Multimedia Spectacle’ -- tFurther Reading -- tSection 8: Advertising and Promotional Culture -- tIntroduction -- t56 ‘Advertising: The Magic System’ -- t57 ‘Advertising, Magazine Culture, and the “New Man”’ -- t58 ‘Soft-soaping Empire: Commodity Racism and Imperial Advertising’ -- t59 ‘The Promotional Condition of Contemporary Culture’ -- t60 ‘Social Communication in Advertising’ -- tFurther Reading -- tSection 9: New Technologies, New Media? -- tIntroduction -- t61 ‘Cyberspace and the World we Live in’ -- t62 ‘The Work of Being Watched: Interactive Media and the Exploitation of Self-Disclosure’ -- t63 ‘The MP3 as Cultural Artifact’ -- t64 ‘Beyond Anonymity, or Future Directions for Internet Identity Research’ -- t65 ‘Cultural Studies and New Media’ -- tFurther Reading -- tAcknowledgements -- tIndex of Names -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMedia Studies: A Reader introduces a full range of theoretical perspectives through which the media may be explored, analysed, critiqued, and understood. The Reader reaches back to essential statements from writers such as Raymond Williams, Stuart Hall, Marshall McLuhan, Jürgen Habermas, Jean Baudrillard and Michel Foucault, whose work was central to forming the field. It also includes wide ranging work on contemporary media formations from a stellar collection of diverse theorists, including Annabelle Sreberny, Paul Gilroy, Charlotte Brunsden, Angela McRobbie, Asu Askoy and Kevin Robins, Micheal Bull, and Nick Couldry, to name only a very few of those included. Finally, the Reader looks to the future, exploring new media formations and their significance, through the work of Mark Andrejevic, Lev Manovich, Jonathan Sterne and others.The sixty-five readings are divided into two main parts: 'Studying the Media' begins with a section on key theoretical perspectives and follows this with five sections opening up questions around the Public Sphere, Representation, Feminism and Gender, Audiences, and Everyday Life respectively. The second part, 'Case Studies', brings together concrete examples of how theoretical approaches can be realised through a series of case studies, covering for instance, reality TV, news, advertising, and new media.With easy-to-follow introductions and guides to further reading accompanying each section, Media Studies: A Reader equips the student to engage with key debates in the field.This new edition updates all sections with a rich selection of contemporary writing complementing re-chosen media 'classics'. In addition: further Reading lists have been comprehensively updated; introductory essays to each section have been expanded and re-written; internal layouts have been completely redesigned for ease of use.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMass mediazGreat Britain. 0aMass media. 4aFilm, Media & Cultural Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Popular Culture.2bisacsh1 aAdorno, Theodor W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAksoy, Asu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAndrejevic, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAng, Ien, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarker, Martin, econtributor.4c